The fix is to replace this with `JsonDocument.Parse()` and manual extraction of the "id" property:

```csharp
private string GetOperationId(RehydrationToken? rehydrationToken)
{
    if (rehydrationToken is null)
    {
        return null;
    }
    var data = ModelReaderWriter.Write(rehydrationToken, ModelReaderWriterOptions.Json, AzureResourceManagerContext.Default);


```

Parsing the JSON document and extracting the id property...

For `ArmClientBuilderExtensions.cs`, the issue is that `RegisterClientFactory<TClient, TOptions>(TConfiguration)` from Azure.Core has `[RequiresUnreferencedCode]` and `[RequiresDynamicCode]` attributes. Since this is calling an Azure.Core API, I need to either add those same attributes to the calling method or find an alternative approach.

Since this is a public API method, adding `[RequiresUnreferencedCode]` and `[RequiresDynamicCode]` is the right choice - it propagates the requirement to callers, which is correct since the method fundamentally requires dynamic configuration binding. Let me apply these fixes across the codebase.
